A.3 RS+GIS Applications in Land Use Planning
n Change Detection — Monitoring LULC Transitions:
Multi-date satellite imagery classifies land cover at two or more time points. GIS overlay identifies pixels
that changed class. Transition matrices show how much forest converted to agriculture, or agriculture to
built-up. Example: India lost 15% of its forest cover between 1990–2015 (tracked by NRSC biennial
reports). Critical for EIA baseline studies.
n Agricultural Land Use Planning:
LULC maps identify available agricultural land, irrigated vs rainfed areas, fallow land and
encroachments. GIS overlay with soil maps, groundwater maps and agro-climatic zones helps plan
optimal cropping zones. India's National Agricultural Land Use Policy uses RS/GIS data.
n Master Plan / Town Planning:
Urban planners use RS-derived LULC maps as base maps for Master Plans. GIS analysis identifies
developable land, green spaces, water bodies, heritage zones and hazard zones. Helps zone areas for
residential, commercial, industrial, recreational use.
n Encroachment Detection:
Comparing current satellite imagery with authorised land use plans identifies illegal encroachments on
forest land, riverbanks, coastal zones and public land. Used by courts and government for enforcement.
n Eco-Sensitive Zone Delineation:
Buffers around protected areas are mapped using GIS. Land use within buffers is assessed from RS
imagery. Activities incompatible with conservation (mining, industries, resorts) are identified for
regulation.
