SECTION B : URBAN SPRAWL DETECTION AND URBAN
MANAGEMENT
Urban sprawl refers to the uncontrolled, rapid and low-density expansion of urban areas into surrounding
rural and natural land. It is driven by population growth, rural-urban migration, industrialisation and poor
land use planning. RS and GIS are the primary tools for detecting, monitoring and managing urban sprawl.
B.1 RS Techniques for Urban Mapping
n Built-up Index (NDBI):
NDBI = (SWIR - NIR) / (SWIR + NIR). Positive values indicate built-up areas. SWIR band is strongly
reflected by concrete, asphalt and metal roofs. Used to map urban extent and monitor annual
expansion.
n Urban Index (UI):
UI = (SWIR - NIR) / (SWIR + NIR). Variant of NDBI. High values in densely built-up areas; negative in
vegetated areas.
n Land Surface Temperature (LST):
Derived from Thermal Infrared (TIR) band of LANDSAT/MODIS. Urban areas have significantly higher
LST than vegetated surroundings (Urban Heat Island = UHI effect). LST maps identify heat-stressed
zones within cities — critical for public health and urban greening planning.
n Impervious Surface Mapping:
Impervious surfaces (roads, buildings, parking lots) prevent water infiltration. RS classifies impervious
vs pervious (vegetated, soil) surfaces. Higher impervious surface % ® more runoff ® flooding ® water
stress. Used for stormwater management planning.
n Night-time Light (NTL) Imagery:
VIIRS/DMSP satellite sensors detect artificial light at night. NTL data tracks urban growth, economic
activity, electrification and informal settlements. India's electrification progress tracked through NTL.
n High Resolution Imagery:
Cartosat-3 (0.25m), WorldView-3 (0.3m) provide building-level mapping. Used for slum identification,
infrastructure assessment, property tax mapping and Smart City planning.
