E.2 Soil and Land Degradation Assessment
n Soil Erosion Mapping:
Erosion hotspots identified by RS indicators: bare soil exposure (low NDVI, high SWIR reflectance),
gully formation (visible in high-res imagery), rill patterns. RUSLE (Revised Universal Soil Loss Equation)
model uses GIS layers: rainfall erosivity (R), soil erodibility (K), slope-length (LS), cover management (C
from NDVI), support practice (P). India: ICAR-NBSS&LUP; maps soil erosion at national scale.
n Desertification Monitoring:
UGC NET Environmental Sciences (Code 89) | Unit I – 1.7 | Page 12
Long-term NDVI decline + vegetation cover decrease + surface albedo increase = desertification
indicators. MODIS 16-year NDVI time series tracks desertification progress in Rajasthan, Gujarat, parts
of AP. UNCCD (UN Convention to Combat Desertification) uses RS for Land Degradation Neutrality
(LDN).
n Waterlogging and Salinity Detection:
Waterlogged areas appear bright in SAR; SWIR bands sensitive to soil salinity (salt crusts have
distinctive reflectance). IRS imagery used to map waterlogged areas in canal commands of
Punjab/Haryana. Saline soils mapped using SWIR–NIR ratio.
n Land Degradation Neutrality (LDN):
SDG 15.3.1 indicator — uses RS-derived metrics: land cover change, NDVI-based soil organic carbon
change, and land productivity. Countries monitor progress toward zero net land degradation by 2030.
E.3 Marine and Fisheries Resource Management
n Potential Fishing Zone (PFZ) Advisories:
INCOIS (Indian National Centre for Ocean Information Services) uses Ocean Colour (chlorophyll-a
concentration) from MODIS-Aqua/OCEANSAT-3 and Sea Surface Temperature (SST) from
AVHRR/MODIS to identify zones of high fish aggregation. Daily PFZ advisories issued to fishermen —
reduces search time, saves fuel, increases catch. Covers India's entire EEZ.
n Coral Reef Monitoring:
Multispectral imagery distinguishes healthy coral (high reflectance in blue-green), bleached coral and
algae-covered reef. WorldView-3, Sentinel-2 used for Lakshadweep and Andaman reefs. Temperature
threshold from NOAA Coral Reef Watch — bleaching when SST exceeds Degree Heating Weeks
(DHW) threshold.
n Mangrove Mapping:
Mangroves have unique spectral signatures: high NIR reflectance, low red reflectance. Classified using
Resourcesat-2 LISS-IV (5.8m). India's mangrove cover (FSI 2021): 4,992 km² (increased by 17 km²
since 2019). GIS overlays mangrove patches with coastal development plans.
n Sea Surface Temperature (SST) Mapping:
AVHRR (Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer) and MODIS thermal bands map global SST.
ENSO monitoring (El Niño/La Niña); Indian Ocean Dipole; upwelling zones; cyclone intensity prediction
(warm SST fuels cyclones).
