SECTION F : WASTE MANAGEMENT APPLICATIONS
While waste management is often considered a ground-level activity, RS and GIS provide powerful tools
for planning, siting, monitoring and regulating waste facilities. This is an emerging application area
increasingly tested in UGC NET.
F.1 RS and GIS in Solid Waste Management
n Landfill Site Selection using GIS:
GIS multi-criteria analysis identifies optimal landfill locations by integrating: land use (avoid
agriculture/forest/residential), soil permeability (avoid high permeability near aquifers), slope (<5%
preferred), distance from settlements (>500m), distance from roads (<2km for accessibility),
groundwater depth, wind direction (away from population). Weighted overlay of all criteria ® suitability
map. Used in most Indian cities under Swachh Bharat Mission.
n Monitoring Existing Landfills:
High-resolution satellite imagery monitors landfill area extent over time. Thermal infrared detects heat
from decomposing waste (methane generation). NDVI decline around landfills indicates leachate
contamination of vegetation. SAR can detect surface subsidence and methane gas emissions.
n Illegal Dumping Detection:
Change detection using high-resolution imagery (before/after) identifies new waste dumps in
unauthorised locations. Spectral signatures of fresh waste (white/grey on imagery) distinguished from
soil and vegetation. GPS coordinates provided to enforcement agencies.
n Waste Generation Estimation:
GIS overlay of population density, income levels, commercial activity with empirical per-capita waste
generation rates ® spatial waste generation model for city planning. Helps design optimal collection
routes and transfer station locations.
n Collection Route Optimisation:
GIS network analysis optimises waste collection vehicle routes — minimises distance, avoids
bottlenecks, maximises coverage. Used in smart waste management systems with IoT bin sensors.
n E-Waste Zone Identification:
GIS mapping of industrial clusters, electronics markets, repair shops and informal e-waste recycling
areas. Buffer analysis identifies residential exposure zones. Used for e-waste collection drive planning
and health impact assessment.
n Bio-Medical Waste Management:
GIS maps healthcare facilities, their waste generation and proximity to common bio-medical waste
treatment facilities (CBWTFs). Identifies under-served areas requiring new CBWTFs. Enforced under
Bio-Medical Waste Management Rules, 2016.
