G.2 RS+GIS for Climate Change Adaptation and Mitigation
n Carbon Sequestration Monitoring:
RS-derived forest biomass (LiDAR + SAR + optical) estimates carbon stored. Annual forest cover
change × carbon density = carbon flux. India's forest carbon stock estimated at 7,204 million tonnes
COn equivalent (FSI 2021). This supports India's NDC target of creating additional carbon sink of 2.5–3
billion tonnes.
n Renewable Energy Site Assessment:
Solar irradiance maps (from MODIS/NASA POWER) + cloud cover frequency ® solar energy potential
maps. Wind speed maps (from scatterometer data) ® wind energy potential. GIS overlay with land use,
grid proximity, slope ® optimal site selection. MNRE uses RS/GIS for India's 500 GW renewable
energy target siting.
n Extreme Event Monitoring:
Cyclone tracking (INSAT meteorological satellites), flood mapping (Sentinel-1 SAR), drought monitoring
(NDVI + LST + rainfall anomaly), heatwave mapping (LST from LANDSAT/MODIS). Early warning
systems save lives and property.
n Coastal Vulnerability Assessment:
RS maps: shoreline change (multi-date high-res imagery), coastal land use, elevation (LiDAR/DEM),
mangrove cover. GIS overlay ® Coastal Vulnerability Index (CVI). Identifies coasts at high risk from sea
level rise and storm surge. India: NIOT maps coastal vulnerability for all districts.
n Urban Heat Island Mitigation Planning:
LST maps identify hot spots in cities. NDVI shows green cover deficiency. GIS analysis links LST to
