H.2 Practice Questions (UGC NET / JRF Pattern)
[MCQ] Which spectral index is most appropriate for detecting open water bodies?
(a) NDVI (b) NDBI (c) NDWI (d) NBR
3 Answer: (c) NDWI = (Green-NIR)/(Green+NIR). Positive values indicate water. NDVI detects vegetation;
NDBI detects built-up; NBR detects burn severity.
[MCQ] MODIS satellite detects active forest fires using which wavelength?
(a) Visible (0.5 mm) (b) NIR (0.8 mm) (c) Thermal IR (~3.9 mm and 11 mm) (d) Microwave
3 Answer: (c) Fires emit strongly at thermal wavelengths (~3.9 mm and 11 mm). MODIS provides fire alerts 4
times/day. VIIRS (375m) is even more accurate.
[MCQ] The Normalized Burn Ratio (NBR) uses which two bands?
(a) Red and NIR (b) NIR and SWIR (c) Green and NIR (d) Blue and SWIR
3 Answer: (b) NBR = (NIR - SWIR) / (NIR + SWIR). High NIR = healthy vegetation; high SWIR =
burned/bare. dNBR (pre-post fire) measures burn severity.
[MCQ] India's FASAL project uses remote sensing for:
(a) Flood mapping (b) Forest fire detection (c) Crop area and production forecasting (d) Glacier monitoring
3 Answer: (c) FASAL = Forecasting Agricultural output using Space, Agro-meteorology and Land based
observations. Uses IRS AWiFS and Sentinel-2 NDVI for crop forecasting before harvest.
[MCQ] Which satellite data is used for sea level rise monitoring?
(a) MODIS (optical) (b) LANDSAT (multispectral) (c) Jason-3/Sentinel-6 (radar altimetry) (d) Cartosat
(panchromatic)
3 Answer: (c) Radar altimetry measures sea surface height to centimetre accuracy. Jason series
(1992–present) shows ~3.7 mm/year rise. Sentinel-6 is the latest altimetry satellite.
[MCQ] Shannon's Entropy in GIS is used to measure:
(a) Forest biomass (b) Degree of urban sprawl (c) Soil salinity (d) Glacier retreat rate
UGC NET Environmental Sciences (Code 89) | Unit I – 1.7 | Page 18
3 Answer: (b) Shannon's Entropy H = -S Pi×ln(Pi) quantifies urban sprawl pattern. High H =
dispersed/sprawling city; Low H = compact city. Used in urban growth analysis.
[MCQ] INCOIS uses ocean colour data primarily for:
(a) Coral bleaching mapping (b) Sea level measurement (c) Potential Fishing Zone (PFZ) advisory (d)
Tsunami prediction
3 Answer: (c) INCOIS issues daily PFZ advisories to Indian fishermen using chlorophyll-a (from
MODIS-Aqua/OCEANSAT) and SST. Reduces search time and fuel costs.
[MCQ] Which model uses GIS layers including rainfall erosivity (R), soil erodibility (K),
slope-length (LS), cover (C) and practice (P) to estimate soil loss?
(a) SWAT model (b) RUSLE (Revised Universal Soil Loss Equation) (c) Streeter-Phelps (d) SCS-CN model
3 Answer: (b) RUSLE: Soil loss = R × K × LS × C × P. C factor derived from NDVI (satellite data). GIS
integrates all layers. Output: tonnes of soil lost per hectare per year.
[MCQ] The difference between Land Cover and Land Use is that:
(a) Land cover is measured in the field; land use by satellite (b) Land cover is what physically exists; land use
is how humans use it (c) They are the same thing (d) Land use is measurable by RS; land cover requires field
surveys
3 Answer: (b) Land cover = physical surface (forest, water, bare soil). Land use = human activity
(agriculture, residential, conservation). Same area can have forest cover but conservation land use.
[MCQ] GIS multi-criteria weighted overlay is used in waste management for:
(a) Tracking individual waste vehicles (b) Landfill site selection (c) Measuring methane emissions (d) Sorting
recyclable materials
3 Answer: (b) Landfill siting uses weighted overlay of: land use, slope, soil type, groundwater depth, wind
direction, distance from settlements and roads to identify the most suitable location.
